\begin_layout Standard
Pre-treatment characteristics are often used to demonstrate balance between
 treatment and control groups.
 The third column in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Balance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 compares differences between treatment and the relevant control groups
 for the two main comparisons we will make (Similar tables for the other
 hypotheses can be found in Appendix Tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Balance1AB"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Balance2AB"

\end_inset

).
 We find statistically significant differences for some characteristics
 between treatment and control groups for the hypothesis related to empowering
 women with information (Model 1 in the upper panel of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Balance"

\end_inset

).
 Joint orthogonality is rejected as well (F-statistic = 3.40; p-value = 0.001).
 This apparent imbalance for the first treatment, however, can be explained
 by the fact that the gender of the respondent at baseline is confounded
 with the treatment, as baseline questions were asked to the person that
 was targeted in the treatment.
 In other words, at least half of respondents to baseline questions in the
 treatment group were women, while all respondents in the control group
 were men.
 Most likely, the significant differences are a reflection of disagreement
 between the male and female co-heads in survey data that has been documented
 in a variety of settings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "doi:10.1086/703082"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is consistent with the fact that we do find balance on characteristics
 that are easier to verify by the enumerator, such as the material of the
 wall of the house or the distance to the nearest input provider.
 It is also consistent with the finding that imbalance is worse for model
 1A (in the top panel of Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Balance1AB"

\end_inset

) than for model 1B (bottom panel of Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Balance1AB"

\end_inset

), as in the former comparison the answers from men in the control group
 are compared to answers of women in the treatment group and in the latter
 answers from men in the control group are compared to answers given by
 the couple together in the treatment group.
 For the comparison to test the impact of role model effects, we do not
 find imbalance between the groups (lower panel in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Balance"

\end_inset

) (F-statistic = 0.661; p-value = 0.706).
